author: 60659cfda992013e610f285c46692d28
text: We don't need WG agreement to add something to the tracker.

author: 60659cfda992013e610f285c46692d28
text: In particular, if the author has an outstanding action (ACTION-123) to reply, due 8 days ago.

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: Since when can non-telcon participants be assigned action items?

author: 60659cfda992013e610f285c46692d28
text: What does this have to do with the telco?

author: 0a39f78bcb297ab0ebe8a29c28bfed89
text: Title: ACTION-123 - HTML Weekly Tracker (at www.w3.org)

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: Let me state it differently, did he agree to taking that action item?

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: It's against W3C protocol to assign action items to people who did not agree to taking them.

author: 60659cfda992013e610f285c46692d28
text: I don't know, nor do I think he needs to.

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: Based on experience with the W3C I'd say he has to agree

author: 60659cfda992013e610f285c46692d28
text: But it is ok to add non-chartered stuff to a spec, and then not to reply when asked for th reasons?

author: b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9
text: my 'agreement' to the tracker item assigned to me was that I thought it was against protocol to refuse when Zakim picked me as "victim"

author: 60659cfda992013e610f285c46692d28
text: Ignoring process for a moment (it wasn't me who added the action...)... But if the WG asks the editor why he did something, I think it deserves an answer.

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: You raised the issue two weeks ago. Things take a bit of time

author: 60659cfda992013e610f285c46692d28
text: If Ian has the time to add these four chapters (vcard, icalendar, bibtext, atom), he probably also has time to explain why.

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: If you catch him on IRC you can probably ask if he can prioritize it somewhat if a timely response is important to you

author: 60659cfda992013e610f285c46692d28
text: I think the fact that there's an overdue action on him should be sufficient information that the WG wants feedback.

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: Seems to me that it followed from the microdata use cases / requirements discussion

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: 60659cfda992013e610f285c46692d28, I doubt he even knows an action item is assigned to him

author: 60659cfda992013e610f285c46692d28
text: so he's both not attending telcos *and* not reading the minutes?

author: b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea
text: 60659cfda992013e610f285c46692d28: FWIW I think the answer to the question is "because it allows the use cases of rich drag and drop / clipboard items" to be fulfilled

author: b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea
text: Although obviously that is not an offical answer

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: 60659cfda992013e610f285c46692d28, that seems like quite a leap from not knowing he has an action item

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: (In my experience Ian always does action items on time.)

author: b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea
text: 60659cfda992013e610f285c46692d28: And whilst I think it makes sense to consider taking the specific mocrodata bits out of HTML 5, keeping the D&D stuff would make the specs codependant on each other. So I'm not sure you'd gain much
